{{Infobox recurring event |name=Bris Funny Fest |frequency = Annually |logo=[[File:Bris_Funny_Fest_2016_Avatar.jpg|200px]] |logo_caption=Bris Funny Fest 2016 Logo |location=[[Brisbane]] |country=[[Australia]] |years_active=2016–present |first = 2016 |dates='''2018''': 1-26 August '''2017''': 2-20 August |genre=[[Arts festival]] |website=[http://brisfunnyfest.com BrisFunnyFest.com] }}
'''Bris Funny Fest''' is a fringe [[comedy festival]] held for the first time in September 2016 in [[Brisbane]], [[Australia]].
The festival was started by Kath Marvelley in 2016 as an alternative once it became clear that the annual Brisbane Fringe Festival was not going to be running in 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/brisbanefringefestival/posts/1062889803784570|title=Brisbane Fringe Festival|website=www.facebook.com|language=en|access-date=2017-07-22}}</ref> It is now the second largest comedy festival in [[Queensland]] with over 50 events as part of its 2017 program<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://brisfunnyfest.com/#gallery|title=Bris Funny Fest Shows|website=brisfunnyfest.com|language=en|access-date=2017-07-22}}</ref> featuring bigger acts such as [[Matt Okine]]. It encompasses genres such as [[stand-up comedy]], [[Improvisational theatre]], [[sketch comedy]] and [[musical theatre]] amongst others. It "showcases everything from established international artists to emerging performers putting on a show for the first time".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://brisfunnyfest.com/|title=Bris Funny Fest|website=brisfunnyfest.com|language=en|access-date=2017-07-22}}</ref>
The festival is an open access "[[unjuried]]" festival (the model used by the [[Edinburgh Fringe Festival]]). There is no fee to be part of the festival, with the organisation being managed by a team of volunteers<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://brisfunnyfest.com/Home/Team|title=Bris Funny Fest Team|website=brisfunnyfest.com|language=en|access-date=2017-07-22}}</ref> led in 2017 by [[Steven Morgan]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://stevenmorgan.wales/comedy/|title=Comedy & Acting|date=2016-09-22|work=Steven Morgan|access-date=2017-07-22|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://inputerror.co.uk/features/8909-running-a-festival-in-a-foreign-country|website=InpuTerror.co.uk|title=Running A Festival In A Foreign Country|date=2017-07-27}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://medium.com/@ma0sm/lessons-learned-organising-a-comedy-festival-e71292123e78|website=Medium.com|title=Lessons Learned Organising A Comedy Festival|date=2017-08-09}}</ref> In 2018 it was announced that Adam O'Sullivan was taking over as festival director.
Bris Funny Fest operates in venues all over Brisbane, though the majority of events take place at Heya Bar in [[Fortitude Valley, Queensland]]. Performers are free to approach any venue to host their event, with guidance offered to both performer and venue by the organisers.
== Previous Brisbane Fringe Festival == The Brisbane Fringe Festival ran from 2012 to 2015, co-directed by Kylie Southwell<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.thecreativeissue.com.au/lessons-from-brisbane-fringe-2013/|title=Lessons from Brisbane Fringe 2013|date=2013-10-21|work=The Creative Issue - News for Creatives|access-date=2017-07-22|language=en-US}}</ref> with comedy curation by Scott Black<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.abc.net.au/local/stories/2013/08/20/3829519.htm|title=Brisbane Fringe Comedy Festival|date=2013-08-20|website=www.abc.net.au|language=en-AU|access-date=2017-07-22}}</ref> who now works as an advisor on Bris Funny Fest.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://brisfunnyfest.com/Home/Team|title=Bris Funny Fest Team|website=brisfunnyfest.com|language=en|access-date=2017-07-22}}</ref>
