{{About|the mountain and transmitter|the court cairn|Clermont Cairn}} {{Use dmy dates|date=June 2014}} {{Use Irish English|date=June 2014}} {{Infobox mountain | name = Clermont Carn | other_name = ''Carnán Mhaighréid Nái'' | photo = Clermont 2RN distant.jpg | photo_caption = Clermont Carn transmission site. | elevation_m = 510 | elevation_ref = <ref name="mv"/> | prominence_m = 312 | prominence_ref =<ref name="mv"/> | listing = | language = [[Irish language|Irish]] | location = [[County Louth|Louth]], [[Republic of Ireland|Ireland]] | range = [[Cooley Mountains]] | map = island of Ireland | map_relief = yes | map_caption =Location in Ireland | coordinates = {{Coord|54.080057|-6.321564|display=inline,title}} | topo = | easiest_route = }} [[Image:RTE Transmitter - Clermont Carn. - geograph.org.uk - 687612.jpg|thumb|283px|right|2RN transmission site on Clermont Carn]] '''Clermont Carn''', variously spelt as "Clermont Cairn", "Clairmont Carn/Cairn" and Carnán Mhaighréid Náir in [[Irish language|Irish]] is a 510m <ref name="mv">{{cite web|url=http://mountainviews.ie/mv/index.php?mtnindex=434|title=Cooley Area - Clermont Carn|publisher=MountainViews.ie|accessdate=2008-07-23}}</ref> high peak in the [[Cooley Mountains]] in [[County Louth]], [[Republic of Ireland|Ireland]], which is also home to a main [[2RN (RTÉ Networks)|2RN]] transmission site.<ref name="rte">{{cite news|url=http://www.rte.ie/radio/NE.html |title=RTÉ, Ireland's National Radio Broadcaster |accessdate=2008-07-23 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080526065828/http://www.rte.ie/radio/NE.html |archivedate=26 May 2008 }}</ref>
==Transmission site== This transmission site in [[County Louth]], was opened in 1981 to provide UHF television coverage for the North East of the [[Republic of Ireland]], counties Louth, Meath, and North county Dublin. However, with the site being less than 1&nbsp;km from the border it was clear that this transmitter would be used to provide [[RTÉ]] services into [[Northern Ireland]]. Initially the two channels [[RTÉ 1]] and [[RTÉ 2]] were carried on Ch52 and Ch56 with [[TV3 (Ireland)|TV3]] (Ch66) and [[TG4]] (Ch68) following later. In 1982, a 2M [[Amateur Radio]] Repeater was installed.<ref>{{cite web|last=Dundalk Amateur Radio Society|title=EI2CCR Repeater|url=http://ei7dar.com/repeater.html|publisher=www.ei7dar.com|accessdate=2013-03-07}}</ref> FM radio transmission was also added providing coverage of the five national channels to a wide area.
In 2002 a new cable-stayed mast 120m tall was erected, this greatly improved coverage into Northern Ireland. The existing self-supporting tower was truncated, and is now only used for microwave links and the Amateur Radio Repeater.
[[Digital Audio Broadcasting|DAB]], digital radio broadcasting from Clermont Carn began in 2006 and [[Digital terrestrial television]] (DTT) trials started in 2008.
In common with all [[2RN (RTÉ Networks)|2RN]] transmitters in Ireland, analogue television transmissions from this site ended on 24 October 2012,<ref>{{cite news|title=Analogue consigned to broadcasting history|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/ireland/2012/1025/1224325680199.html|accessdate=2012-06-12|newspaper=The Irish Times|date=2012-10-25}}</ref> but uniquely, Clermont Carn is the only main television transmitter in Ireland that is vertically [[Antenna (radio)#Polarization|polarised]], and does not service any [[Broadcast relay station|relay transmitters]]. Today the Irish digital television service [[Saorview]] is broadcast from here to a sizeable area including a large tract of Northern Ireland, with a good signal being received in [[Belfast]] and beyond. This overspill has been welcomed by the UK’s [[Ofcom]] who have provided information for viewers in Northern Ireland about receiving TG4 and the RTÉ channels, both from within Northern Ireland on the UK's [[Freeview (UK)|Freeview]] service, and via the [[Saorview]] overspill.<ref>{{cite web|last=Ofcom|title=Digital Terrestrial TV Coverage Map of TG4 and RTÉ in Northern Ireland|url=http://consumers.ofcom.org.uk/files/2012/07/NIMuxFactsheet4.pdf|publisher=Ofcom|accessdate=2012-11-06}}</ref>
