The '''Mexcaltitán Ballet''' (native name Ballet Mexcaltitan, Danza y Arte de México) was founded in 1989 by choreographer Sergio Eugenio García Pérez and is based in the western state of [[Nayarit]] in [[Mexico]] .<ref name="secculnay">{{cite web |url=http://www.cecan.gob.mx/ballet_mexcaltitan.php |title=Ballet Mexcaltitan Danza y Arte |publisher=Secretary of Culture, State of Nayarit |location=Nayarit |language=Spanish |accessdate=September 20, 2011 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111111110426/http://www.cecan.gob.mx/ballet_mexcaltitan.php |archivedate=November 11, 2011 |df= }}</ref> It was founded to promote and consolidate Mexican folk dance, with a focus on the state of Nayarit, making it unique.<ref name="secculnay"/><ref name="21años">{{cite news |title=21 años del ballet Mexcaltitán |url=http://www.revistaopcion.com/2010/10/09/21-anos-del-ballet-mexcaltitan/ |newspaper=Revista Opción |location=Mexico |date=October 9, 2010 |accessdate=September 20, 2011 |language=Spanish |trans-title=21 years of the Mexcaltitán Ballet |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120322180819/http://www.revistaopcion.com/2010/10/09/21-anos-del-ballet-mexcaltitan/ |archivedate=March 22, 2012 |df= }}</ref> However, the troupe also performs other dance from [[Latin America]] and contemporary dance as well as Mexican styles. The dancers are young and trained by the company to perform.<ref name="21años"/> The organization is divided into two sections, the main group and a children’s group called the Mexcaltitán Infantil, geared to very young dancers with the aim of training them to become part of the main group.<ref name="entusiasta">{{cite news |title=Entusiasta la participación del Ballet Mexcaltitán |author=Lorena Rodríguez Roja |url=http://impreso.milenio.com/node/9027501 |newspaper=El Eco de Nayarit |location=Nayarit, Mexico |date=September 16, 2011 |accessdate=September 20, 2011 |language=Spanish |trans-title=Enthusiastic participation by the Mexcaltitán Ballet |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120401032816/http://impreso.milenio.com/node/9027501 |archivedate=April 1, 2012 |df= }}</ref> Today, the troupe is supported by the Nayarit state government and García Pérez remains as the general director.<ref name="uchile">{{cite web |url=http://balletantumapu.uchile.cl/V2/festival-2011/mexico/  |title= México, Mexcaltitan.  |publisher=University of Chile |location=Santiago |language=Spanish |accessdate=September 20, 2011 }}</ref>

While its main objective is to train young dancers in [[Folk dance of Mexico|traditional Mexican folk dance]], it also trains artists in other disciplines such as acting and singing, with the aim of further promoting Mexican and Nayarit culture.<ref name="secculnay"/><ref name="21años"/> This allows the organization to create larger theatrical pieces such as a homage to [[Francisco Gabilondo Soler]], who performed radio shows for children in the 20th century.<ref name="dellibro">{{cite press release |title= Ballet Mexcaltitán participa en la Feria Internacional del Libro de Miami como parte de la delegación coordinada por Conaculta |publisher=[[CONACULTA]] |date=November 18, 2010 |url= http://www.conaculta.gob.mx/sala_prensa_detalle.php?id=9508 |language=Spanish |trans-title=Mexcaltitán Ballet participates in the Miami International Book Fair as part of the delegation coordinated by Conaculta |accessdate=September 20, 2011 }}</ref> In 2011, the group presented a program called Legends and Traditions of Old Nayarit in honor of choreographer Jaime Buentello Bazán. This production focused on the stories, dance and music of the state in times past, especially those areas along the coast.<ref name="espectacular">{{cite news |title=Espectacular noche de gala del Ballet Mexcaltitán |author=Robín Zavala |url=http://cronicanayarita.com.mx/?p=1810 |newspaper=Crónica de Nayarit |location=Nayarit, Mexico |date=August 3, 2011 |accessdate=September 20, 2011 |language=Spanish |trans-title=Spectaular gala night of the Mexcaltitán Ballet |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120402170810/http://cronicanayarita.com.mx/?p=1810 |archivedate=April 2, 2012 |df= }}</ref>

The ensemble has performed in its native Nayarit and other parts of Mexico such as [[Guadalajara, Mexico|Guadalajara]], [[Cancún]], and the [[Palacio de Bellas Artes]] in [[Mexico City]] .<ref name="21años"/><ref name="dellibro"/> The ensemble has toured in Europe, Asia and the Americas in countries such as France, Spain, [[Belgium]], Germany, [[Switzerland]], England, [[Taiwan]], [[Dominican Republic]], [[Argentina]], [[Chile]], [[Peru]], [[Honduras]], [[Guatemala]], [[El Salvador]], [[Cuba]], [[Brazil]], [[India]], [[Canada]] and the United States.<ref name="secculnay"/> Festivals in which it has performed include [[Festival Internacional Cervantino]], Encuentro Internacional de Folklore "Antumapu" at the [[University of Chile]] in [[Santiago]] in 2011,<ref name="azteca21">{{cite news |title="Ballet Mexcaltitan, Danza y Arte", participa en Chile en el Encuentro Internacional de Folklore "Antumapu"  |url= http://azteca21.com/n/index.php/news/15070-qballet-mexcaltitan-danza-y-arteq-participa-en-chile-en-el-encuentro-internacional-de-folklore-antumapuq |newspaper=Azteca 21 |location=Mexico City |date=August 18, 2011 |accessdate=September 20, 2011 |language=Spanish |trans-title=Ballet Mexcaltitan participates in Chile at the Antumapu International Folklore Encounter }}</ref><ref name="eleco">{{cite news |title=Participa el Ballet Mexcaltitán en encuentro internacional folklórico |url=http://www.elecodenayarit.net/ediciones/2011/08/18/06.pdf |newspaper=El Eco de Nayarit |location=Nayarit, Mexico |date=August 18, 2011 |accessdate=September 20, 2011 |language=Spanish |trans-title=Mexcaltitán Ballet participates in international folk dance encounter |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120402170810/http://www.elecodenayarit.net/ediciones/2011/08/18/06.pdf |archivedate=April 2, 2012 |df= }}</ref>  and the [[Miami Book Fair International]] in [[Florida]] .<ref name="dellibro"/> The group states that the dances of [[Jalisco]] receive the most attention abroad and most readily identify the group as Mexican.<ref name="dellibro"/>

